<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12008g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12008g">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12008g"> 8(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Realise himself <font face="wake">C</font> <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12008g"><li>FW 487.18 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n12008g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n12008g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12008g">MS BL 47484a-42</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:177 <a name="rAd4" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rAd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd4.htm#n12008g">Draft: III&sect;3A.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Je vous passe le reste qui est moins int&eacute;ressant, car il ne vous &eacute;tonnera pas que M. Cl&eacute;dat juge parfaitement normal <i>invectiver quelqu&apos;un</i>, puisque &ldquo;la langue offre de multiples exemples de transitifs indirects transform&eacute;s en transitifs directs&rdquo;, et qu&apos;il ne trouve pas bien grave que le subjonctif perde, hormis la troisi&egrave;me, toutes les personnes de son imparfait. Il ne dit pas, mais il aurait pu dire que r&eacute;aliser, au sens nouveau qu&apos;on donne &agrave; ce verbe, bien loin d&apos;&ecirc;tre un anglicisme, est un archa&iuml;sme scolastique: c&apos;est l&apos;anglais to realize qui est un gallicisme; F&eacute;nelon dit d&apos;ailleurs, dans ses <cite>Lettres spirituelles</cite>: &ldquo;Je comprends sans peine que l&apos;&acirc;ge et les infirmit&eacute;s vous font regarder la mort de pr&egrave;s: cette m&ecirc;me vue rapproche et <i>r&eacute;alise</i> tristement l&apos;objet&hellip; <i>R&eacute;aliser</i> a exactement ici le sens contraire &agrave; celui d&apos;<i>id&eacute;aliser</i>&hellip; Et moi aussi, je suis philologue! <br><font color="green">[The rest will be less interesting since it will not surprise you that M. Cl&eacute;dat thinks that it is perfectly normal to say <i>invecter quelqu&apos;un</i>, because &ldquo;language offers many examples of indirect transitives that have become direct transitives&rdquo;, and he does not mind much that the subjunctive has lost, apart from the third person, all the other persons of its imperfect. He does not, but he could also mention that <i>r&eacute;aliser</i>, in the new sense given to this verb, is not an anglicism but a scholastic archaic form: it is the English verb <i>to realize</i> that is a Gallicism; F&eacute;n&eacute;lon writes in his <cite>Lettres spirituelles</cite>: &ldquo;I understand without trouble that age and infirmity have given you the chance to look death in the eye: this sight brings the object in a sad manner closer and <i>realize</i> it &hellip; <mark><i>R&eacute;aliser</i> is here the opposite of <i>id&eacute;aliser</i>.</mark> And I am a philologist too!&rdquo;]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 115</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
